<a href="http://falkvinge.net/2011/05/19/the-information-policy-case-for-flat-tax-and-basic-income/#comment-83948">
May 19, 2011 - 11:52</a> </div>
<p>Soctrap is completely right. It is a well established fact within economics that VAT is a regressive tax. According to <a href="http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_social/Taxes-Benefits-2007-2008/Taxes_benefits_0708.pdf" rel="nofollow">UK national statistics </a> (page 5) the poorest 20% of the population pays 10.5% of their income in VAT, while the richest 20% pays only 4,5% of their income in VAT. The reason, of course, is that savings and investments do not get taxed. So those people who can&#8217;t afford to save money, but has to use all their salary on food, rent etc. will be taxed very hard.</p>
<div class="reply">
<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/05/19/the-information-policy-case-for-flat-tax-and-basic-income/?replytocom=83948#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-83948", "83948", "respond", "7361")'>RESPOND TO THIS</a> </div>
