<li class="comment even depth-3" id="li-comment-83949">
<div id="comment-83949">
<div class="commentnumber">2.1.2</div>
<div class="comment-author vcard">
<div class="avatar-commentnumber"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/54a19e1e2c696e2f62b5e941bea40a8b?s=60&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D60&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60'/></div> <cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.socialtrap.org' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>soctrap</a></cite> </div>
<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
<a href="http://falkvinge.net/2011/05/19/the-information-policy-case-for-flat-tax-and-basic-income/#comment-83949">
May 19, 2011 - 11:53</a> </div>
<p>The Marginal propensity to Consume is what I am referring to. High income earners don&#8217;t &#8220;consume&#8221; all their income and more importantly, not at the moment it is earned (goes to savings, assets, investments, inheritance). The difference isn&#8217;t small, </p>
<p>You then state that governments will be unable to see wealth, such as property, investments, assets etc. That IS weatlh. The means of exchange (cash, krone, dollar etc) are not wealth, but simply the means we use to exchange wealth.</p>
<p>The asset poor individual can only become asset rich by using personal wealth such as education, initiative, labour etc. </p>
<p>I am not trashing your argument by pointing these things out. The &#8220;citizens salary&#8221; (or making basic food, shelter, health, communication, education, water, air, security etc all a basic human right for everybody) is spot on&#8230;</p>
