</div>
</li> 
<li class="comment byuser comment-author-rickfalkvinge bypostauthor even depth-2" id="li-comment-83978">
<div id="comment-83978">
<div class="commentnumber">17.2</div>
<div class="comment-author vcard">
<div class="avatar-commentnumber"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3d0f5f0abb40ac682e9ea7c9e5e4410b?s=60&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D60&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60'/></div> <cite class="fn">Rick Falkvinge</cite> </div>
<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
<a href="http://falkvinge.net/2011/05/19/the-information-policy-case-for-flat-tax-and-basic-income/#comment-83978">
May 19, 2011 - 15:59</a> </div>
<p>As for taxes and terminology, we need to keep our definitions straight here.</p>
<p>A flat tax rate is, <b>by definition</b>, neither progressive nor regressive.</p>
<p>However, it can have effects that harm the less fortunate more, in the same way that a regressive tax does (but obviously not as much). I argue that it has such effects, and that those effects need to be offset. But that&#8217;s no reason to call it regressive, because it isn&#8217;t.</p>
<div class="reply">
<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/05/19/the-information-policy-case-for-flat-tax-and-basic-income/?replytocom=83978#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-83978", "83978", "respond", "7361")'>RESPOND TO THIS</a> </div>
